'Object-oriented'¶

Procedural v objects¶

"Object-oriented design requires that you shift from thinking of the world as a collection of predefined procedures to modeling the world as a series of messages that pass between objects"

  • Sandi Metz, Practical Object-Oriented Design in Ruby

Gift to future self¶

Encapsulates data and behaviour into classes¶

What is a class?¶

The blueprint for an object

In [6]:
class Cat():
  def __init__(self, name, colour, disposition):
    self.name = name
    self.colour = colour
    self.disposition = disposition

What is an object?¶

An instance of a class

In [7]:
cat = Cat('Captain Tiddles', 'brown', 'mild-mannered')
print(cat.name)
print(cat.colour)

Captain Tiddles
brown

Why is this useful?¶

Imagine you are managing a petshop, and a customer requests a particular sort of cat...

In [9]:
class Inventory(): 
    def __init__(self): 
        self.pets = []
        
    def add_pet(self, animal): 
        self.pets.append(animal)
        
    def filter_pets(self, disposition): 
        return [pet.name for pet in self.pets if pet.disposition == disposition]
        
inventory = Inventory()
inventory.add_pet(cat)
print(inventory.filter_pets('mild-mannered'))

['Captain Tiddles']

Define classes¶

In [13]:
class Feature(): 
    def __init__(self, name): 
        self.name = name
        self.linregress_coeffs = self.get_stats()
        self.p_value = self.linregress_coeffs.pvalue
        self.r_value = self.linregress_coeffs.rvalue
    
    def get_stats(self): 
        mask = (-target.isna()) & (-results_and_demographics[self.name].isna())
        return stats.linregress(target[mask], results_and_demographics[self.name].loc[mask])
In [15]:
class CorrelationFinder(): 
    def __init__(self, sort_by='p_value'): 
        self.features = []
        self.ARBITRARY_NUMBER_OF_FEATURES = 40
        self.sort_by = sort_by
        
    def add(self, feature): 
        self.features.append(feature)
        
    def get_top_features(self): 
        reversed_sort_needed = self.sort_by == 'r_value'
        sorted_features = sorted(self.features, 
                                 key=lambda feature: getattr(feature, 
                                                             self.sort_by), 
                                 reverse=reversed_sort_needed
                                )
        return sorted_features[:self.ARBITRARY_NUMBER_OF_FEATURES]
        
    def plot_top_features(self): 
        for feature in self.get_top_features():
            print(feature.name)
            print('correlation coefficient is:', feature.r_value)
            print('p value is:', feature.p_value)
            sns.scatterplot(results_and_demographics[feature.name], target, 
                            hue=results_and_demographics['winner'], 
                            palette={'gop': 'red', 'dem': 'blue'}, alpha=0.1)
            df_sorted = results_and_demographics.sort_values(feature.name, ascending=False).head(ARBITRARY_NUMBER_OF_COUNTIES)
            print(df_sorted['winner'].value_counts())
            sns.scatterplot(df_sorted[feature.name], df_sorted[target_var_name], 
                            hue=df_sorted['winner'], 
                            palette={'gop': 'red', 'dem': 'blue'})
            plt.show()
